In this Sanhita, unless the context otherwise requires—

(1) 'act' denotes as well a series of acts as a single act;

(2) 'animal' denotes any living creature, other than a human being;

(3) 'child' means a person who has not completed eighteen years of age;

(4) 'counterfeit' — A person is said to 'counterfeit' who causes one thing to resemble another thing, intending by means of that resemblance to practise deception, or knowing it to be likely that deception will thereby be practised;

(16) 'Government' denotes the Central Government or a State Government;

(18) 'injury' denotes any harm whatever illegally caused to any person, in body, mind, reputation or property;

(22) 'public servant' — The words 'public servant' denote a person falling under any of the descriptions hereinafter following.

(1) Whoever, except in the cases provided for in sub-section (2), commits rape, shall be punished with rigorous imprisonment of either description for a term which shall not be less than ten years, but which may extend to imprisonment for life, and shall also be liable to fine.

(2) Whoever—
(a) being a police officer, commits rape;
(b) being a public servant, commits rape;
(c) being a member of the armed forces;
(d) being on the management or on the staff of a jail, remand home or other place of custody;
(e) being a relative, guardian or teacher of, or a person in a position of trust;
(f) commits rape during communal or sectarian violence;
(g) commits rape on a woman knowing her to be pregnant;
shall be punished with rigorous imprisonment for a term which shall not be less than ten years, but which may extend to imprisonment for life.

**Note:** Corresponds to IPC Section 376. BNS consolidates S.376, 376A, 376B, 376C, 376D provisions.

Whoever commits culpable homicide not amounting to murder shall be punished with imprisonment for life, or imprisonment of either description for a term which may extend to ten years, and shall also be liable to fine, if the act by which the death is caused is done with the intention of causing death, or of causing such bodily injury as is likely to cause death;

or with imprisonment of either description for a term which may extend to ten years, or with fine, or with both, if the act is done with the knowledge that it is likely to cause death, but without any intention to cause death, or to cause such bodily injury as is likely to cause death.

**Note:** Corresponds to IPC Section 304.

(1) Whoever commits organised crime shall,—
(a) if such act has resulted in the death of any person, be punished with death or imprisonment for life, and shall also be liable to fine which shall not be less than ten lakh rupees;
(b) in any other case, be punished with imprisonment for a term which shall not be less than five years but which may extend to imprisonment for life, and shall also be liable to fine which shall not be less than five lakh rupees.

**Explanation:** For the purposes of this section,—
(i) 'organised crime' means any continuing unlawful activity including kidnapping, robbery, vehicle theft, extortion, land grabbing, contract killing, economic offence, cyber crimes, trafficking in persons, drugs, weapons or illicit goods or services, human trafficking for the purpose of prostitution or ransom, by any person or a group of persons acting in concert, either singly or jointly, as a member of an organised crime syndicate or on behalf of such syndicate, by use of violence, threats, intimidation, coercion, or by any other unlawful means;

**Note:** Section 111 is an entirely new provision in BNS with no direct IPC equivalent. It specifically addresses organised crime syndicates, filling a gap that previously required special legislation like MCOCA.

The following kinds of hurt only are designated as 'grievous':—

First — Permanent privation of the sight of either eye;

Secondly — Permanent privation of the hearing of either ear;

Thirdly — Privation of any member or joint;

Fourthly — Destruction or permanent impairing of the powers of any member or joint;

Fifthly — Permanent disfiguration of the head or face;

Sixthly — Fracture or dislocation of a bone or tooth;

Seventhly — Any hurt which endangers life or which causes the sufferer to be during the space of twenty days in severe bodily pain, or unable to follow his ordinary pursuits.

**Note:** Corresponds to IPC Section 320. The BNS omits 'emasculation' as a category of grievous hurt (previously First in IPC S.320).
